# Tonic Design Invariants

*MonoGlide Matrix (MGM) — Tonic Architecture Draft*

This document defines architectural invariants, not implementation details.

The implementation may evolve, but these invariants should remain stable unless there is a compelling musical reason to revise them.
---

# Purpose

Tonic is not simply another note priority mode.

Unlike traditional monophonic note priority algorithms, Tonic interprets a
performance as two independent musical roles:

- Foundation
- Voice

These roles are dynamically assigned throughout a performance and are
independent of the physical notes being played.

Once assigned, Foundation and Voice operate as separate monophonic performers
sharing a common keyboard input while maintaining independent transition
behavior.

This role-based architecture is intended to produce more musical, predictable,
and extensible behavior than traditional monophonic priority systems.

---

# Design Philosophy

The primary goal of Tonic is not to determine *which note wins*.

Instead, its purpose is to interpret a player's musical intent by separating a
performance into two complementary musical roles:

- Foundation
- Voice

The resulting behavior should feel natural to musicians rather than exposing
implementation details.

Performance choices should describe musical outcomes rather than technical
parameters.

---

# Tonic Design Invariants

## Invariant 0 — Roles, Not Notes

Foundation and Voice are independent musical roles, not note identities.

Notes may assume or relinquish either role dynamically throughout a performance.

No note permanently owns either role.

---

## Invariant 1 — One Foundation

There shall never be more than one active Foundation.

---

## Invariant 2 — One Voice

There shall never be more than one active Voice.

---

## Invariant 3 — Independent Performers

Foundation and Voice behave as independent monophonic performers.

Neither performer should directly manipulate the musical behavior of the other.

---

## Invariant 4 — Foundation Independence

Foundation transitions shall never directly retrigger, restart, or interrupt the
Voice.

Changing Foundation should affect only Foundation.

---

## Invariant 5 — Voice Independence

Voice transitions shall never directly retrigger, restart, or interrupt the
Foundation.

Changing Voice should affect only Voice.

---

## Invariant 6 — Deterministic Role Assignment

Role assignment must always be deterministic.

The same performed notes should always produce the same Foundation and Voice
assignment regardless of transition timing.

Transition behavior must never influence role assignment.

Role assignment always occurs first.

---

## Invariant 7 — Direction Independence

Ascending and descending melodic motion should behave identically.

The engine should never depend upon melodic direction.

---

## Invariant 8 — Independent Transition Policies

Foundation and Voice may use different transition policies.

Current planned Foundation transition policies:

- TNC Pedal
- TNC Smooth

Current Voice transition policy:

- User-selected Transition Mode
- User-selected Transition Time

Future Foundation transition policies may be added without requiring changes to
the underlying Tonic architecture.

